def info_file(condition, no_file):
    if condition == 'habituated':
        if no_file > len(filenames_habituated):
            raise ValueError("Habituated does not contain that number of cells!!")
        else:
            print('Filename: ' + filenames_habituated[no_file])
            print('')
            print('Contains the means of: ' + str(list(freq_h[0].iloc[:,no_file]))
                  + ' In total: ' + str(np.nansum(list(freq_h[0].iloc[:,no_file]))) + ' APs')
            print(ind_h[no_file])     

    if condition == 'baseline':
        if no_file > len(filenames_baseline):
            raise ValueError("Baseline does not contain that number of cells!!")
        else:
            print('Filename: ' + filenames_baseline[no_file])
            print('')
            print('Contains the means of: ' + str(list(freq_b[0].iloc[:,no_file])) + ' In total: ' 
                  + str(np.nansum(list(freq_b[0].iloc[:,no_file]))) + ' APs')
            print(ind_b[no_file])
        
    else:
        raise ValueError('No such condition!!')

Time alignment and threshold¶

There are some published ways of defining the threshold, for exploration. I took the steepest initial change of the derivative.

In [12]:
# Find just the most abrupt change in the derivative (Threshold of the AP)
def threshold_ap_pos(V, abs_no):
    dy = np.diff(V)/1 # Derivative
    mean_peak_start = abs(dy) > abs_no; # <--- Changes bigger than abs_no, returns 1 and 0.
    changes_pos = np.nonzero(mean_peak_start); # Only those that have changes.
    threshold_AP_pos = changes_pos[0][0]; #I am only interested in the first abrupt change.
    return threshold_AP_pos;

abs_no =  0.3 #<----- This was the one that worked the best! Lower won't be real.

# Threshold for each dataset.
thr_habituated = []
thr_baseline = []
for ii in range(0, len(V_h)):
    thr_habituated.append(threshold_ap_pos(V_h[ii],abs_no));
for ii in range(0, len(V_b)):
    thr_baseline.append(threshold_ap_pos(V_b[ii],abs_no));

# Aligning based on threshold:

size_vec = 1200 
thr_ideal_pos = 600

V_h_adj = []
V_b_adj = []

def adjust_thr_time(V,thr_real_pos,thr_ideal_pos,size_vec):
    V_adj = np.pad(V,((thr_ideal_pos-thr_real_pos),1000),mode='constant',constant_values=(np.nan,np.nan))
    V_adj.resize(size_vec)
    return V_adj

[V_h_adj.append(adjust_thr_time(V_h[ii],thr_habituated[ii],thr_ideal_pos, size_vec)) for ii in range(len(V_h))]
[V_b_adj.append(adjust_thr_time(V_b[ii],thr_baseline[ii],thr_ideal_pos, size_vec)) for ii in range(len(V_b))]

Still trying to understand the right units.

# Making the derivative dV/dt
fs = 20000
def phase_vector(V,fs):
    dV = np.diff(V, axis = 0)
    #dt = np.diff(t)
    dV_dt = []
    dV_dt = dV/fs
    dV_dt = np.insert(dV_dt,0,dV_dt[0])
    return dV_dt

# For each dataset:
dV_dt_h = []
dV_dt_b = []

for ii in range(len(V_h)):
    dV_dt_h.append(phase_vector(V_h_adj[ii], fs))

    dV_dt_b.append(phase_vector(V_b_adj[ii], fs))

def duration_AP(V, abs_no):
    dy = np.diff(V)/1 # Derivative
    mean_peak_start = abs(dy) >= abs_no
    changes_pos = np.nonzero(mean_peak_start) # Only those that have changes.
    changes_pos = [item for sublist in changes_pos for item in sublist]
    return changes_pos, changes_pos[-1]

# Changes for each dataset.
changes_habituated = {}
changes_baseline = {}
end_AP_habituated = {}
end_AP_baseline = {}

for ii in range(0, len(V_h_adj)):
    np.warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
    changes_habituated[ii], end_AP_habituated[ii] = duration_AP(V_h_adj[ii],abs_no)
    
for ii in range(0, len(V_b_adj)):
    np.warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
    changes_baseline[ii], end_AP_baseline[ii] = duration_AP(V_b_adj[ii],abs_no)
    
changes_habituated = np.array(list(changes_habituated.values()))
changes_baseline = np.array(list(changes_baseline.values()))

# Half-widths

# Imagine there is a curve and 10 datapoints, the mirror opposite of the one in the rise side was slightly higher than the decay one, 
# because of the number of datapoints. So I interpolated the signal so that I have more datapoints
# and the nearest on the other side is closer to the truth. 
# Uses scipy.signal.resample

xtimes = 10 #<------ #This number divided by two is how many new datapoints per datapoint,
# use 1 to see how it looks without resampling. Pair numbers work better.
# Because the vector was padded to align for threshold, there are some nans in the signal. 
# So I removed those. Ideally xtimes < 12

lim = 300
resample_length = int((lim * 2) * xtimes)
thr_position = thr_ideal_pos # Threshold position from adjusted = 600
V_h_adj_x = []
V_b_adj_x = []

for ii in range(0, len(V_h_adj)):
    V_h_adj_x.append(resample(V_h_adj[ii][(thr_position - lim):(thr_position + lim)],resample_length));
for ii in range(0, len(V_b_adj)):
    V_b_adj_x.append(resample(V_b_adj[ii][(thr_position - lim):(thr_position + lim)],resample_length));

#t_x = resample(t[(thr_position - lim_l):(thr_position + lim_r)], resample_length) 
t_x = np.linspace(t[thr_position- lim],t[thr_position+ lim],resample_length)

thr_position_x = int(resample_length/2) # Threshold position from adjusted = 600
factor = int(thr_position_x/thr_position)

print('The signal was upsampled ' + str(factor) + ' times') #How many datapoints per previous datapoint.

# I also need to recalculate the new end_APs: work in progress...
end_AP_habituated_x = []; end_AP_baseline_x = []
[end_AP_habituated_x.append((end_AP_habituated[ii]*(factor))) for ii in end_AP_habituated];
[end_AP_baseline_x.append((end_AP_baseline[ii]*(factor))) for ii in end_AP_baseline];

# Now the half-widths..

def find_nearest(array, value): #this function is already in abfun, for the nans is re-written.
    array = np.array(array) # Converts the array in numpy if it is not.
    idx = np.nanargmin(np.abs(array - value)) #Given array, searches value, and finds the closest position.
    return idx

def find_half_id(V, end_AP, thr_position):
    peak = np.nanargmax(V)  #Find the peak.
    half_id_v = V[peak] - ((V[peak] - (V[thr_position])) / 2) # end of the AP minus the peak in voltage
    half_id_v_p = find_nearest(V[thr_position:peak], half_id_v)
    half_id_pos_l = thr_position + half_id_v_p
    #half_id_v1 = find_nearest(V[0:peak], half_id_v0)
    half_id_val = V[half_id_pos_l]
    half_id_pos_r0 = find_nearest(V[peak:-1], half_id_val) # Now this voltage should be found in position left.
    #half_id_pos_r1 = find_nearest(V[peak:-1], half_id_val) # Matching to the right.
    half_id_pos_r = peak + half_id_pos_r0 # But the right requires the addition of the peak.
    return [half_id_pos_l, half_id_pos_r] # return both sides. (Threshold and end AP)

half_id_h = []
half_id_val_h = []
half_id_b = []
half_id_val_b = []

for ii in range(len(V_h_adj_x)):
    half_id_h.append(find_half_id(V_h_adj_x[ii], end_AP_habituated_x[ii], thr_position_x)); #finds it in the habituated
for ii in range(len(V_b_adj_x)):

# Find 10% and that. Rise:
# This one uses the regular vector, no resampling was needed.

def find_10_90_rise(V, thr):
    peak = np.nanargmax(V)  #Find the peak.
    id_10_v = int(((V[peak]-((V[thr]))) * 10) / 100) # Find in voltage
    id_90_v = int(((V[peak]-((V[thr]))) * 90) / 100)
    rise_10_p = V[thr] + id_10_v #add that to the threshold
    rise_90_p = V[thr] + id_90_v   
    rise_10_p2 = find_nearest(V[thr:peak], rise_10_p)# Find which position is that one. 
    rise_90_p2 = find_nearest(V[thr:peak], rise_90_p)
    rise_10_pos = thr + rise_10_p2 #Add that position to threshold.
    rise_90_pos = thr + rise_90_p2  
    return [rise_10_pos, rise_90_pos, peak]

# Same story but for decay:
# Requires that you know your end AP, as defined above.

def find_10_90_decay(V, end_AP_pos):
    peak = np.nanargmax(V)  #Find the peak.
    id_10_v = int(((V[end_AP_pos]-((V[peak]))) * 10) / 100) # Find in voltage
    id_90_v = int(((V[end_AP_pos]-((V[peak]))) * 90) / 100)
    decay_10_p = V[peak] + id_10_v #add that to the threshold
    decay_90_p = V[peak] + id_90_v   
    decay_10_p2 = find_nearest(V[peak:end_AP_pos], decay_10_p)# Find which position is that one. 
    decay_90_p2 = find_nearest(V[peak:end_AP_pos], decay_90_p)
    decay_10_pos = peak + decay_10_p2 #Add that position to threshold.
    decay_90_pos = peak + decay_90_p2  
    return [decay_10_pos, decay_90_pos, peak]

In [41]:
#Since some voltage vectors are shorter and adjusted by thr on the x axis. 
# It is not possible at the moment to adjust on the y-axis by the beginning of the prepotential.

def align_y_voltage(V1_x_adj,V2_x_adj,reference):
    a = V1_x_adj[reference]; b = V2_x_adj[reference]
    y_adj_val = abs(a - b)
    V1_xy_adj = []
    V2_xy_adj = []
    if a > b:
        V2_xy_adj = V2_x_adj
        V1_xy_adj = V1_x_adj
        idx = np.where(~np.isnan(V1_x_adj))
        for ii in range(0, len(idx)):
            V1_xy_adj[idx]=V1_xy_adj[idx[0]] - y_adj_val
    else:
        V1_xy_adj = V1_x_adj
        V2_xy_adj = V2_x_adj
        idx = np.where(~np.isnan(V2_x_adj))
        for ii in range(0, len(idx)):
            V2_xy_adj[idx]=V2_xy_adj[idx[0]] - y_adj_val
    return V1_xy_adj
